# motoquencer: editing the four step pitches on the faders, then clocking to
# prove per-step CV playback and the motorized position readback (expect F<n>).
#
# Scale = C lydian, two octaves (quantize=2, cvbase=0, cvrange=0.2). The pitch
# fader has one notch per scale note: 15 notes across 0..0.2 V, so notch k rests
# at position k/14 and plays the k-th allowed semitone. Allowed semitones (from C):
#   idx0=0(C,0V) idx3=6(F#,0.05) idx7=12(C+1oct,0.1) idx14=24(C+2oct,0.2).
# The first tick is a warm-up so the circuit takes ownership of the faders (motor
# recall); user moves are read from the next tick on.
tickrate 100
patch <<<
[m4]
[motoquencer]
    clock = I1
    cv    = O1
    gate  = O2
>>>
@0 expect O1 0 tol 1e-4
# tick1: edit the four steps to distinct notches. The motor snaps each fader to the
# notch rest position, read back with expect F<n>.
@1 move F1 0.0
@1 move F2 0.5
@1 move F3 1.0
@1 move F4 0.2142857
@1 expect F1 0.0 tol 1e-4
@1 expect F2 0.5 tol 1e-4
@1 expect F3 1.0 tol 1e-4
@1 expect F4 0.2142857 tol 1e-4
# clock through the four steps: cv follows each step's pitch.
@2 set I1 1
@2 expect O1 0.0 tol 1e-4
@3 set I1 0
@4 set I1 1
@4 expect O1 0.1 tol 1e-4
@5 set I1 0
@6 set I1 1
@6 expect O1 0.2 tol 1e-4
@7 set I1 0
@8 set I1 1
@8 expect O1 0.05 tol 1e-4
@9 set I1 0
# wrap back to step 0
@10 set I1 1
@10 expect O1 0.0 tol 1e-4
